In the logical equation, F represents a False value and r can either be True or False. Additionally, anything AND False (&F) will also be False, because for "AND" operation to be True, both values need to be True. If one is False, the result is False.

So, your expression can be simplified as below:

(!((!F)&((r&r)&(r&F))))
= (!((T)&((r&r)&F))) {since !F is True}
= (!((T)&F)) {since r&F is False}
= (!F) {since T&F is False}
= T {since !F is True}

So, the simplified value of the given expression is T (True).
